Yes. Then the standard needs to be much harsher.

If this is a programming language, not "structured notes for an LLM," then I would reverse several of my earlier instincts.

You should treat CDI as:
	•	strictly parsed
	•	whitespace and symbol sensitive where intended
	•	unforgiving by default
	•	validated before execution
	•	edited with tooling, not trust

In that frame, typos do kill the thing. And that is not a flaw. It is the price of having an exact language.

The question becomes: how do you keep the language exact without losing the Beast goals of readability, composability, and LLM-editability?

The right mental model

Not markdown.
Not YAML.
Not "human-readable config."

Closer to:
	•	Python 2
	•	Makefile
	•	shell
	•	old-school DSLs
	•	languages where syntax is part of the discipline

So the rule is:

CDI must be pleasant to read, but it must behave like code.

That means a few consequences follow immediately.

1. Comments and executable syntax must be completely distinct

Your use of #intent: and #note: is fine, but only if the parser treats them as truly non-semantic comments.

There should be zero ambiguity between:
	•	syntax the machine consumes
	•	comments humans and LLMs read

So this is good:

#intent: generate neutral pose sprite
$$$generate-sprite

But only if #... is guaranteed dead to the parser.

If comments ever influence parsing implicitly, the language gets dangerous fast.

2. The sigil hierarchy is valid, but only if it is fully formal

If:
	•	$$$$ means pipeline
	•	$$$ means generator
	•	$$ means section
	•	$ means field/variant spread

then that must be a hard grammar rule, not just a convention.

That means:
	•	$$$$$ must either have a defined meaning or be illegal
	•	$$$ inside the wrong parent scope must error
	•	a $field must only appear where allowed
	•	repeated or missing levels must be syntax errors

In other words: do not let the parser "figure it out."

3. Reserved tokens should be short, exact, and closed

If this is code, then long symbolic phrases like:

+beast-concatenate-comma

are not too verbose because of LLM fragility. They are too verbose because programming languages benefit from compact, exact reserved words.

You want something more like:

+join_comma
+join_newline
+null

or with your prefix discipline:

+b2_join_comma
+b2_join_newline
+b2_null

That is more language-like.

A language should have a small, closed vocabulary of builtins.

4. Misspellings should fail immediately and loudly

You said it exactly: typos kill the whole thing.

So yes:
	•	spirtes.db and spirteify-colors should not be tolerated
	•	no fuzzy matching
	•	no auto-correction in the language core
	•	no parser guesswork

Tooling can help humans, but the language should stay strict.

That means Beast2 needs:
	•	parser
	•	linter
	•	formatter
	•	syntax highlighter
	•	maybe autocomplete

The tooling can be forgiving.
The language should not be.

5. Your language needs a real grammar document now

Not just examples. A grammar.

At minimum, you need to define:
	•	lexical tokens
	•	comment syntax
	•	identifier rules
	•	section nesting rules
	•	reserved keywords
	•	literal forms
	•	operator forms
	•	pipeline chaining semantics
	•	whether newlines are semantic
	•	whether indentation is semantic
	•	whether blank lines are ignored
	•	whether duplicate fields are legal
	•	what order constraints exist

If you do not define these, people will write "CDI-like text," not CDI.

6. Newlines probably need to be semantically meaningful

Because your whole design is about low punctuation and high readability, I suspect CDI should treat newline as significant in the way Python does.

That would be very Beast.

Something like:
	•	one declaration per line
	•	continuation only through explicit nesting/context
	•	comments ignored
	•	blank lines optional separators

That keeps it readable without falling into punctuation soup.

7. The language should separate structure from evaluation

Right now your sample mixes:
	•	declaration
	•	variant lists
	•	join behavior
	•	artifact flow

That is fine, but only if semantics are crisp.

For example, a $character block should mean something exact, such as:
	•	a named variant axis
	•	whose child lines are candidate values
	•	whose following modifier lines affect assembly behavior until the next sibling block

If that is the model, write it down that way.

Languages become solid when every construct has a single job.

8. "LLM-friendly" must mean tooling- and style-friendly, not syntax-loose

This is the crucial correction.

If CDI is a programming language, then you should not bend syntax to make LLMs comfortable.

Instead:
	•	keep syntax exact
	•	give LLMs abundant comments and examples
	•	require them to output syntactically valid CDI
	•	validate every edit mechanically

That is how programmers use exact languages with imperfect generators.

In other words:

the LLM adapts to CDI, CDI does not adapt to the LLM past readability choices.

That is the right power relationship.

9. I would keep your sigils

Given what you just said, I would actually keep the sigils. They now make more sense.

Because if this is code, then:
	•	$$$$ as pipeline
	•	$$$ as generator
	•	$$ as section
	•	$ as axis/setting

is not decorative. It is grammar.

And it has real advantages:
	•	fast visual parsing
	•	compactness
	•	strong hierarchy markers
	•	easy grep/search
	•	easy voice naming conventions

That is perfectly legitimate for a DSL.

10. The real question is whether context-sensitive parsing is worth it

Your language can go one of two ways:

Option A: strongly context-sensitive

Meaning of a line depends heavily on parent block.

Pros:
	•	compact
	•	elegant
	•	Beast-like

Cons:
	•	harder parser
	•	harder tooling
	•	harder error messages

Option B: more explicit per node type

Each block declares what it is more redundantly.

Pros:
	•	easier parser
	•	easier tooling
	•	clearer diagnostics

Cons:
	•	more verbose
	•	less elegant

Given your goals, I think you want A with just enough explicitness to keep parsing sane.

So not markdown, not JSON, but a strict concise DSL with hard contextual grammar.

What I would recommend now

You are at the point where examples are no longer enough. I would write the spec in this order:

1. Lexical rules

Define:
	•	comments start with #
	•	identifiers allowed chars
	•	sigil tokens
	•	path literal rules
	•	numeric literal rules
	•	string rules, if any
	•	newline handling

2. Block grammar

Define exactly what:
	•	$$$$name
	•	$$$name
	•	$$name
	•	$name
	•	+keyword
	•	-> artifact ->

mean and where each may appear.

3. Variant expansion semantics

Define how options combine.
This is the heart of the language.

4. Evaluation semantics

Define execution order, caching, artifact passing, and failure behavior.

5. Error model

Define what errors are syntax vs semantic vs runtime.

That gives you a real language.

One clean philosophical line

You could put it this way in the spec:

CDI is not a markdown convention for describing pipelines. CDI is a strict programming language for defining reproducible Beast systems. Human readability is a design goal, not a relaxation of syntax.

That feels like the correct stance.

Concrete implication for your draft

Your current sample should be reviewed like code:
	•	spelling errors are real bugs
	•	reserved words need exact canonical forms
	•	every token needs formal legality
	•	comments are commentary only
	•	parser behavior must be deterministic

So yes, I’d revise my frame completely:

not "help the LLM muddle through,"
but "design an exact DSL that can be linted, formatted, parsed, compiled, and only then executed."

That is much stronger.

The next right move is to write a formal CDI grammar sketch from your current draft, not more prose examples.











