From your notes and examples, I think the core of CDI should be stated much more bluntly:

CDI is code

CDI is not markdown.
CDI is not prose with structure.
CDI is not "best effort" text for an LLM to interpret.

CDI is a strict linear programming language for defining reproducible Beast pipelines.

Its priorities are:
	•	exact syntax
	•	exact reproducibility
	•	complete embedded provenance
	•	linear execution
	•	low parser complexity
	•	human readability as a bonus, not an excuse for ambiguity

That means your philosophy can be written pretty cleanly.

⸻

Beast CDI: core principles

1. Parameter name and assignment are not on the same line

This is unusual, but coherent.

It gives you:
	•	cleaner scanning
	•	clearer variant blocks
	•	easier multi-value expansion
	•	less punctuation noise

So instead of:

width = 1024

you want something like:

$resolution
1024*1024

or equivalent.

That is a legitimate language design choice. It should be treated as grammar, not style.

⸻

2. A single CDI fully reproduces the work

This is one of the strongest ideas in the whole Beast system.

A CDI should contain enough information to reproduce the artifact exactly, including things like:
	•	checkpoint filename
	•	checkpoint size
	•	checkpoint hash
	•	loras
	•	seed sources
	•	resolution
	•	workflow steps
	•	output database / artifact targets
	•	variant definitions

That makes CDI closer to:
	•	a build file
	•	a workflow spec
	•	an artifact lineage contract

than a prompt file.

This is where Beast becomes unusually strong.

⸻

3. Linear execution is a feature, not a limitation

You said:
	•	no goto
	•	no nested ifs
	•	maybe one if/else later
	•	currently no conditionals

I think that is wise.

A lot of systems get weaker when they become "real programming languages" too early.
Your strength is that CDI appears to be heading toward:
	•	declarative
	•	linear
	•	variant-driven
	•	pipeline-oriented

That is enough power for a huge amount of Beast use.

So the official stance should probably be:

CDI is intentionally less expressive than a general programming language in order to remain legible, reproducible, and safe to mutate.

That’s strong language.

⸻

4. Published artifacts should embed CDI

This is probably the most important design choice you’ve made.

When an output image, video, or asset contains either:
	•	full CDI
	•	or the single realized variant CDI
	•	plus exact model references and hashes

then the artifact becomes self-describing and reproducible.

That is civilization-memory thinking. It is very aligned with the Beast axioms.

I would elevate this from "expected" to almost a law:

A Beast artifact is strongest when it carries the instructions of its own making.

⸻

5. Most users should never see CDI

This is also right.

The Photoshop-style UI is the product.
CDI is the substrate.

So CDI should be designed for:
	•	exactness
	•	tooling
	•	serialization
	•	reproducibility
	•	AI-assisted editing

not for casual users to hand-author every day.

Some power users will write it directly.
Most people will manipulate it through UI.

That means the language can afford to be stricter than a consumer-facing format.

⸻

What your two drafts suggest

Your uploaded files already show a useful separation.

The "spell language" doc

This is really about:
	•	command surface
	•	conceptual compression
	•	user-facing invocation
	•	books / shelves / spells
	•	system identity and metaphor

That is closer to the top interaction layer.

The "Prompt DSL Specification" doc

This is much more like a sub-language:
	•	line start rules
	•	reserved prefixes
	•	section/snippet structure
	•	simple combinatorics
	•	parser in a few hundred lines of C

That is an excellent candidate for the embedded prompt layer inside CDI.

So I would not merge these blindly. I would formalize the stack:

Proposed Beast language stack

Layer 0: Voice / CLI spells

Short commands:
	•	conj goblin
	•	rend video
	•	judge case

These invoke existing systems.

Layer 1: Prompt DSL

Tiny line-oriented prompt composition language:
	•	sections
	•	snippets
	•	concat operators

Used inside generators.

Layer 2: CDI

Full artifact/pipeline language:
	•	generators
	•	sections
	•	model metadata
	•	seeds
	•	resources
	•	outputs
	•	lineage
	•	linear chaining

That hierarchy feels right.

⸻

The most important distinction: prompt text vs executable structure

Your prompt DSL draft has a strong rule:
	•	every line begins with $, #, or b2_

That is excellent for the Prompt DSL.

But CDI may need a slightly different rule set, because it is not just composing prompt text. It is also defining:
	•	workflows
	•	resources
	•	artifact outputs
	•	variant axes
	•	step chaining

So I would resist the temptation to force the exact same lexical discipline onto both layers unless it truly helps.

The real design goal should be:

Prompt DSL should be extremely easy to mutate.
CDI should be extremely hard to misinterpret.

Those are different goals.

⸻

A clean CDI philosophical statement

Here is the version I think your docs are reaching for:

Beast CDI

Beast CDI is a strict, linear, reproducibility-first programming language for defining Beast generators and pipelines.

It is designed so that:
	•	a parser can be implemented simply
	•	a formatter and linter can be authoritative
	•	every artifact can carry the exact instructions of its own creation
	•	UI systems can generate CDI without losing power
	•	local LLMs can edit CDI under strict validation

CDI is not a general-purpose language.
It intentionally avoids complex control flow in favor of:
	•	linear execution
	•	explicit variant expansion
	•	durable artifact lineage
	•	exact environment specification

That’s the core.

⸻

Strong recommendations from your philosophy

Based on everything you’ve shown, I would lock these in:

Keep
	•	strict syntax
	•	linear structure
	•	explicit variant axes
	•	embedded provenance
	•	comments ignored by parser
	•	small parser target in C
	•	UI-first usage model

Avoid
	•	fuzzy syntax
	•	"natural language but structured" ambiguity
	•	nested control flow
	•	hidden defaults that reduce reproducibility
	•	runtime behavior that cannot be serialized back into CDI

That last one matters a lot:
if the UI can do something CDI cannot represent exactly, CDI loses authority.

⸻

One very important law to add

You’re already close to this, but I’d say it plainly:

CDI must be the canonical form.

Not:
	•	UI as truth
	•	JSON as truth
	•	internal graph as truth

But:
	•	CDI is truth
	•	UI edits CDI
	•	engine executes CDI
	•	artifacts embed CDI
	•	JSON, if used, is an implementation detail

That one decision would make Beast much stronger.

⸻

Suggested formal split in your docs

