Beast CDI v0.1 Specification

Beast Command Document Interface
Status: Draft v0.1
Intent: Strict, linear, reproducibility-first programming language for Beast generators and pipelines.

⸻

1. Purpose

Beast CDI is a strict programming language for defining reproducible Beast generators and pipelines.

CDI exists to solve four problems at once:
	1.	Exact reproducibility
A CDI should contain enough information to fully reproduce a generated artifact.
	2.	Readable structure
A human should be able to inspect a CDI and understand the system shape.
	3.	Toolability
A parser, linter, formatter, validator, and UI should be able to consume and emit CDI deterministically.
	4.	Artifact lineage
A generated artifact may embed full or partial CDI metadata so the artifact carries the instructions of its own making.

CDI is not markdown, not prose, and not a best-effort config format. CDI is code.

⸻

2. Design principles

2.1 Strict syntax

Typos, misspellings, malformed structure, or illegal placement of constructs are errors.

2.2 Linear execution

CDI is intentionally linear.
v0.1 has:
	•	no goto
	•	no loops
	•	no nested conditionals
	•	no conditionals at all

Variant selection may be controlled by UI or runtime options, but the document itself remains linear.

2.3 Parameter name and assignment are not on the same line

A parameter declaration introduces a named axis, setting, or field.
Its values appear on subsequent lines.

2.4 Full reproducibility

A CDI should be able to encode exact model provenance, including:
	•	filename
	•	size
	•	hash
	•	resource path or resource identity
	•	all parameters needed for recreation

2.5 Canonical source of truth

CDI is the canonical representation of a Beast pipeline or generator.
UI, JSON, internal graphs, and metadata exports are secondary representations.

2.6 Comments are non-semantic

Comments exist for humans and AI tools only.
They must have no effect on parsing or execution.

⸻

3. Language layers

Beast CDI v0.1 may embed or reference other Beast language layers, but is itself the top-level execution language.

Recommended conceptual stack:
	•	Spell / command surface: short invocation layer
	•	Prompt DSL: prompt-composition sublanguage
	•	CDI: full pipeline language

This document defines CDI only.

⸻

4. Document model

A CDI document is a sequence of lines.
The language is line-oriented.

A CDI document consists of nested blocks using sigil-prefixed headers:
	•	$$$$name → pipeline
	•	$$$name → generator
	•	$$name → section
	•	$name → field / axis / setting
	•	+keyword → modifier / reserved directive
	•	-> target -> → linear artifact handoff

These forms are grammar, not style.

⸻

5. Lexical rules

5.1 Encoding

CDI source files must be UTF-8.

5.2 Newlines

Newlines are significant.
Each declaration occupies exactly one logical line.

5.3 Blank lines

Blank lines are allowed and ignored.

5.4 Comments

Any line whose first non-whitespace character is # is a comment line and is ignored by the parser.

Examples:

#intent: generate a neutral sprite
#note: comments are ignored by execution

5.5 Leading whitespace

Leading whitespace on semantic lines is ignored in v0.1.
Indentation is not semantic.

5.6 Trailing whitespace

Trailing whitespace is ignored.

5.7 Case sensitivity

All identifiers, keywords, and reserved words are case-sensitive.

5.8 Identifiers

Identifiers used after sigils must match this rule:
	•	first character: a-z
	•	remaining characters: a-z, 0-9, -, _, .

Examples of valid identifiers:

pixel-art-pipeline
generate-sprite
positive-prompt
sdxl-beast.apr2026

Examples of invalid identifiers:

GenerateSprite
generate sprite
13-seed


⸻

6. Top-level grammar

A valid CDI document must begin with exactly one pipeline header.

6.1 Pipeline

$$$$pipeline-name

A pipeline is the top-level execution container.

6.2 Generator

$$$generator-name

A generator must appear inside a pipeline.

6.3 Section

$$section-name

A section must appear inside a generator.

6.4 Field

$field-name

A field must appear inside a section.

6.5 Modifier

+keyword

A modifier applies within the current valid scope, as defined by that keyword.

6.6 Artifact handoff

-> target ->

An artifact handoff line connects the current generator’s output to the next stage or storage target.

⸻

7. Structural rules

7.1 Valid nesting

Valid structural nesting in v0.1:
	•	pipeline contains generators
	•	generator contains sections
	•	section contains fields
	•	field contains values and modifiers valid for that field
	•	generators may contain artifact handoff lines
	•	comments may appear anywhere

7.2 Invalid nesting

These are syntax errors:
	•	field outside section
	•	section outside generator
	•	generator outside pipeline
	•	second pipeline in same document
	•	artifact handoff outside generator
	•	value line without an active field

7.3 Ordering

Order is significant and preserved.

Within a generator:
	•	sections execute in source order
	•	artifact handoff occurs where written

Within a section:
	•	fields are defined in source order
	•	values are read in source order

⸻

8. Value lines

A value line is any non-comment, non-blank line that is not:
	•	a pipeline header
	•	generator header
	•	section header
	•	field header
	•	modifier
	•	artifact handoff

A value line belongs to the most recent active field.

Example:

$checkpoint
sdxl-beast-apr2026.safetensors

Here, sdxl-beast-apr2026.safetensors is a value line belonging to $checkpoint.

⸻

9. Field semantics

In v0.1, a field represents one of two things:
	1.	single-value setting
	2.	multi-value variant axis

The engine determines which by the number of values attached to the field.

9.1 Single-value setting

A field with exactly one value is a single-value setting.

Example:

$checkpoint
sdxl-beast-apr2026.safetensors

9.2 Multi-value variant axis

A field with more than one value is a variant axis.

Example:

$seed
13
666

This creates two variants for the seed field.

9.3 Empty field

A field with zero values is a semantic error unless a future extension defines a null-only field form.

⸻

10. Variant expansion

10.1 Core rule

Within a section, all multi-value fields participate in Cartesian expansion unless a future explicit selection mode overrides this.

If a section contains:
	•	$a with 2 values
	•	$b with 3 values
	•	$c with 1 value

the section expands to 2 × 3 × 1 = 6 combinations.

10.2 Single-value fields

Single-value fields contribute the same value to every expanded variant.

10.3 Variant order

Expanded variants are ordered lexicographically by field appearance order, with each field’s values enumerated in source order.

10.4 Runtime selection

UI or runtime tools may choose to execute:
	•	all variants
	•	one variant
	•	a filtered subset

This does not change the meaning of the source CDI.

⸻

11. Reserved modifiers

Reserved modifiers begin with +.
Unknown modifiers are syntax errors.

v0.1 defines the following core modifiers.

11.1 +b2_null

Marks one value position as an explicit null option.

Example:

$style
+b2_null
blocky and slightly ugly
high quality illustrated beauty

Semantics:
	•	the field has an additional null variant
	•	when null is selected, the field contributes no value
	•	null contributes no join text unless a later rule says otherwise

11.2 +b2_join_comma

Defines the join rule for prompt-like value assembly in the current applicable scope.

11.3 +b2_join_newline

Defines newline join behavior.

11.4 Modifier scope

In v0.1, modifiers apply to the most recent field unless explicitly documented otherwise.

This keeps parsing simple and deterministic.

Example:

$style
+b2_null
blocky and slightly ugly
high quality illustrated beauty
+b2_join_comma

If stricter placement is preferred, the formatter may canonicalize modifiers to appear before or after all values for that field. One canonical style should eventually be chosen and enforced.

⸻

12. Prompt assembly sections

CDI may contain prompt-construction sections whose fields are assembled into a final prompt string.

Example:

$$positive-prompt

$prefix
pixel art in 8 bit retro style
pixel art in 16 bit modern style
+b2_join_comma

$character
a smiling brown haired girl wearing a red hoodie
a very short green goblin with a greedy smile
+b2_join_comma

12.1 Prompt assembly rule

For prompt sections, each field contributes its selected value into a final assembled string according to field-local join behavior.

12.2 Default join behavior

If no explicit join modifier is present, the implementation must choose one documented default.
Recommended v0.1 default: comma.

12.3 Null omission

If a field contains +b2_null and null is selected, the field contributes nothing and does not emit its join token.

⸻

13. Resource provenance

CDI v0.1 should be able to encode full provenance for required resources.

Recommended pattern:

$$model

$checkpoint_name
sdxl-beast-apr2026.safetensors

$checkpoint_size
6932458241

$checkpoint_hash_sha256
abc123...

$checkpoint_path
e:/models/sdxl-beast-apr2026.safetensors

13.1 Reproducibility rule

If a resource materially affects output, CDI should contain enough information to identify it exactly.

13.2 Preferred provenance fields

Recommended fields for model-like resources:
	•	name
	•	size
	•	hash
	•	path or registry identity

A later version may standardize exact reserved field names.

⸻

14. Artifact handoff

Artifact handoff connects stages linearly.

Example:

-> sprites.db ->

14.1 Meaning

The current generator writes its output artifact set to the named target.

14.2 Target

The target is implementation-defined in v0.1, but may refer to:
	•	database
	•	file
	•	artifact store
	•	collection
	•	named intermediate dataset

14.3 Linearity

Artifact handoff does not branch.
It simply passes the produced artifact set forward in source order.

14.4 Multiple handoffs

Multiple handoff lines inside one generator are legal only if the execution model defines them.
Recommended v0.1 rule: one terminal handoff per generator.

⸻

15. Execution model

15.1 Linear execution

Pipelines execute generators in source order.

15.2 Section execution

Within each generator, sections are evaluated in source order.

15.3 No branching

v0.1 has no conditional execution and no loops.

15.4 Variant expansion point

Variant expansion occurs within each section as defined by that section’s fields.

15.5 Artifact persistence

Each generator produces artifacts which may be:
	•	retained
	•	stored
	•	passed forward
	•	embedded into output metadata

Implementation details are outside the language core, but must not contradict CDI semantics.

⸻

16. Metadata embedding

A Beast artifact may embed:
	•	the full CDI
	•	the realized single-variant CDI
	•	selected provenance subset

16.1 Full CDI embedding

Preferred for archival and full reproducibility.

16.2 Realized variant embedding

Useful when a multi-variant source CDI produced one particular artifact.

16.3 Canonical reduction

If embedding a single realized variant, the implementation should reduce each multi-value field to the exact chosen value, preserving overall structure.

⸻

17. Errors

CDI errors fall into three categories.

17.1 Syntax error

Examples:
	•	malformed sigil line
	•	illegal nesting
	•	unknown modifier
	•	invalid identifier
	•	value without active field

17.2 Semantic error

Examples:
	•	empty field
	•	missing required provenance for a strict reproducibility mode
	•	multiple terminal handoffs in a generator if disallowed
	•	illegal field in a known standard section

17.3 Runtime error

Examples:
	•	referenced checkpoint file not found
	•	hash mismatch
	•	generation backend failed
	•	artifact database unavailable

⸻

18. Canonical formatting

CDI should eventually have an authoritative formatter.

Recommended v0.1 formatting rules:
	•	no semantic indentation required
	•	exactly one blank line between major block groups
	•	comments preserved where possible
	•	headers appear flush left
	•	field values appear flush left
	•	modifiers appear flush left
	•	canonical newline at end of file

18.1 Canonical ordering

Canonical ordering should preserve source order rather than reordering semantically equivalent fields.
Source order is meaningful for readability and variant ordering.

⸻

