Beast CDI v0.2 Specification

Status: Draft v0.2
Intent: Strict, linear, artifact-complete programming language for Beast systems

⸻

1. Core Definition

Beast CDI is a strict, line-oriented programming language for defining generators and pipelines of generators.
	•	A generator is the smallest executable unit
	•	A CDI may contain:
	•	a single generator
	•	or multiple generators (a pipeline)

⸻

2. Naming Model

Two interchangeable naming layers exist:

Formal (spec)
	•	generator
	•	pipeline (multi-generator CDI)

Voice / UX
	•	subroutine (generator)
	•	generators (pipeline)

Example voice command:

"run goblin generator"
"run pixel generators"

The language itself uses generator, but tooling may surface either.

⸻

3. Structural Model

$$$$pipeline-name      (optional if only one generator)
$$$generator-name
$$section-name
$field-name
value

Rules
	•	A CDI with one generator does NOT require a pipeline header
	•	A CDI with multiple generators MUST have a pipeline header
	•	Generators execute in source order

⸻

4. Whitespace Semantics (critical)

CDI v0.2 introduces semantic whitespace.

4.1 Leading spaces are significant

Leading spaces in value lines are preserved exactly.

Example:

$word
sub human
subhuman
 sub human

These are three different values:
	1.	"sub human"
	2.	"subhuman"
	3.	" sub human" (leading space preserved)

⸻

4.2 Space as a composition primitive

CDI treats space as a first-class composition operator.

This enables:
	•	sub + human → "sub human"
	•	sub + human (no space) → "subhuman"

⸻

5. Word Composition (NEW v0.2)

This is a major addition.

CDI must support:
	•	prefixes
	•	postfixes
	•	controlled spacing

5.1 Prefix and postfix fields

Example:

$prefix
sub
goblin

$root
human
goblin

$postfix
+ b2_null
king

5.2 Composition rules

Final output is constructed as:

[prefix][space?][root][space?][postfix]

Where:
	•	spacing is explicitly controlled
	•	no implicit spaces are inserted unless defined

⸻

5.3 Explicit spacing control

Introduce:

+b2_join_space
+b2_join_none

Example:

$prefix
sub
+b2_join_none

$root
human

→ result: subhuman

$prefix
sub
+b2_join_space

$root
human

→ result: sub human


⸻

5.4 Third placeholder (required)

You specified:

include a space as the third placeholder

So fields may explicitly include a space value:

$join
""        # no space
" "       # space
"-"       # hyphen

This becomes a composable axis.

⸻

6. Field Semantics

6.1 Field = axis

Each $field defines:
	•	one or more values
	•	optional modifiers
	•	optional join behavior

6.2 Variant expansion

All fields combine via Cartesian product.

⸻

7. Generators

7.1 Definition

A generator is:
	•	a linear transformation
	•	consumes input artifacts
	•	produces output artifacts

7.2 Example

$$$generate-goblin

$$prompt

$prefix
sub

$root
goblin

$postfix
king

-> goblins.db ->


⸻

8. Pipelines (multi-generator CDI)

A pipeline is simply:

$$$$pixel-art

$$$generate-sprite
...

-> sprites.db ->

$$$reduce-palette
...

-> sprites.db ->

No branching. Only linear flow.

⸻

9. Artifact Model

Every generator:
	•	consumes artifacts
	•	produces artifacts

Artifacts may be:
	•	image sets
	•	video
	•	latent tensors
	•	databases
	•	prompt outputs

⸻

10. UI ↔ CDI Law (NEW)

Law: CDI must roundtrip perfectly with UI
	•	every UI action produces valid CDI
	•	every CDI can be loaded into UI without loss

