whats ebnf?








EBNF stands for Extended Backus–Naur Form.

It’s just a compact, formal way to describe the grammar of a programming language.

Think of it as:

the blueprint of what strings are valid code

⸻

Simple intuition

Right now, your CDI spec is written in English:

"a generator contains sections, sections contain fields, fields contain values…"

That’s readable, but not precise enough for:
	•	writing a parser
	•	catching syntax errors exactly
	•	guaranteeing no ambiguity

EBNF turns that into something like:

generator = "$$$", identifier, newline, { section } ;

This means:

a generator = "$$$" + name + newline + zero or more sections

⸻

Why you want EBNF (important for you)

You said:

"this is python 2, exact syntax matters"

Then EBNF is the next step.

Because it gives you:
	•	no ambiguity
	•	machine-checkable rules
	•	parser-ready structure
	•	a way to prove your language is well-defined

Without it, people will implement CDI slightly differently → fragmentation.

⸻

Core symbols (very small set)

You only need a few things:

1. Assignment

a = b ;

means:

"a is defined as b"

⸻

2. Sequence

a = b, c, d ;

means:

b then c then d

⸻

3. Choice

a = b | c ;

means:

either b or c

⸻

4. Optional

a = [ b ] ;

means:

b may or may not appear

⸻

5. Repetition

a = { b } ;

means:

b can repeat 0 or more times

⸻

6. Literal text

a = "$$$" ;

means:

exactly those characters

⸻

Tiny example for CDI

Here’s a very small sketch based on your language:

cdi          = [ pipeline ], generator, { generator } ;

pipeline     = "$$$$", identifier, newline ;

generator    = "$$$", identifier, newline, { section } ;

section      = "$$", identifier, newline, { field } ;

field        = "$", identifier, newline, { value_line | modifier_line } ;

modifier_line = "+", identifier, newline ;

value_line   = text, newline ;

That’s already enough to:
	•	parse structure
	•	enforce nesting
	•	reject invalid files

⸻

What EBNF does NOT do

Important:

EBNF only defines structure, not meaning.

So it won’t say:
	•	how variants expand
	•	how prompts are joined
	•	how pipelines execute

That stays in your semantic spec (what you already wrote).

⸻

Why this matters for Beast

Right now you’re at a critical moment:

You have:
	•	a strong idea
	•	consistent syntax
	•	real examples

The next step is:

lock the grammar so the language cannot drift

If you don’t:
	•	every implementation becomes slightly different
	•	LLM edits become inconsistent
	•	bugs become subtle and painful

⸻

Very direct analogy
	•	Your current doc = Python tutorial
	•	EBNF = Python grammar definition

Both are needed.

