llms are deterministic if flops are ordered correctly on correct hardware








You’re pointing at something real, but it needs to be framed carefully or it’ll lead to false guarantees.

Short version

Yes -- LLMs can be deterministic.
No -- they are not reliably deterministic in practice unless you control more than people usually realize.

⸻

What you’re right about

At the lowest level:

If the exact same sequence of floating point operations is executed in the exact same order on the exact same hardware with the exact same inputs, the result is deterministic.

That’s just physics + IEEE floating point (modulo edge cases).

So in principle:
	•	fixed weights
	•	fixed input tokens
	•	fixed sampling parameters
	•	fixed RNG seed
	•	fixed kernel execution order
	•	fixed hardware
→ same output

That’s true.

⸻

Where it breaks in practice

The moment you leave that idealized environment, determinism leaks.

1. GPU nondeterminism
	•	parallel reductions (sums, softmax)
	•	race conditions in kernels
	•	atomic operations
	•	fused ops reordered by compiler

Even tiny FP differences → different logits → different token sampled.

⸻

2. Kernel implementations differ

Same model, different backends:
	•	CUDA vs TensorRT vs ONNX
	•	different versions of cuDNN
	•	different optimization passes

→ slightly different math → diverging outputs

⸻

3. Hardware differences
	•	RTX 4080 vs 4090
	•	different tensor cores
	•	different precision paths (FP16 vs BF16)

→ different rounding → drift

⸻

4. Sampling amplification

Even if logits differ by 1e-6:
	•	top-k / top-p sampling
	•	temperature scaling

can flip a token choice → completely different output chain

⸻

5. Tokenization + formatting

Even trivial differences:
	•	whitespace
	•	newline handling
	•	prompt construction

→ different token sequence → different output

⸻

The correct Beast framing

You don’t want:

"LLMs are deterministic"

You want:

"LLMs can be made reproducible under controlled execution conditions."

That’s much stronger and more actionable.

⸻

Beast CDI implication (important)

This affects your spec directly.

You need two modes

1. Reproducible mode (strict)

CDI must capture:
	•	model file + hash
	•	tokenizer version
	•	exact prompt (post-assembly)
	•	sampling parameters
	•	RNG seed
	•	backend (CUDA / TensorRT / etc.)
	•	kernel determinism flags
	•	hardware class (or constraint)

Optional but powerful:
	•	logit outputs (for debugging)
	•	full output artifact

⸻

2. Exploratory mode (loose)
	•	temperature variation
	•	multiple models
	•	variant expansion
	•	nondeterministic allowed

⸻

New concept for CDI

Execution guarantees

You could formalize something like:

$b2_execution_mode
reproducible

or

$b2_determinism
strict

Then:

strict mode requirements
	•	must fix seed
	•	must disable nondeterministic kernels
	•	must log environment
	•	must warn on unsupported hardware

⸻

The key Beast insight

For images:

determinism = seed + model + settings

For LLMs:

determinism = entire execution stack

That’s the difference.

⸻

What Beast can do that others don’t

You’re already halfway there with CDI.

You can define:

Artifact truth vs recompute truth

Artifact truth
	•	store output
	•	always exact
	•	no recompute needed

Recompute truth
	•	regenerate
	•	must match (if deterministic mode)

Beast should treat:

artifact as ground truth, recompute as verification

That matches your UX:

delete → import CDI → regenerate → verify

