Yes. This is a strong architecture. It preserves the Beast pattern:

fast path for simple commands, inspectable drafted system for complex ones, and full lineage all the way down.

What you’re really describing is not "voice control with AI." It is a compiler pipeline for spoken intent.

⸻

Beast Voice Pipeline

General-purpose command system with LLM assist

Core principle

A spoken command should not disappear into a black box.

It should move through explicit stages:
	•	speech
	•	transcript
	•	parse
	•	classification
	•	lookup
	•	CDI draft
	•	UI preview
	•	execution

Each stage should produce an artifact.
Each artifact should be inspectable, replayable, and reproducible.

So if something goes wrong, the user or developer can ask:
	•	was the transcript wrong?
	•	was the command actually short and should have hit pure C?
	•	was the parser wrong?
	•	was the lookup context wrong?
	•	did the LLM draft bad CDI?
	•	did the UI misrepresent the draft?
	•	did execution diverge from the CDI?

That is exactly the Beast way to do it.

⸻

Top-level flow

Your current flow is already good:

voice input
-> v2 text
-> .c parser short-command check
-> lookup / prompt generation
-> llm drafts cdi
-> ui preview
-> execution

I would tighten it into this canonical pipeline:

voice audio
-> transcript artifact
-> command parse artifact
-> route decision artifact
-> optional local lookup artifacts
-> llm draft prompt artifact
-> drafted cdi artifact
-> ui preview/edit state
-> approved cdi artifact
-> execution artifacts

That gives each stage a distinct responsibility.

⸻

The two-lane model

This system should have two explicit lanes.

Lane 1: pure C fast path

For extremely short, obvious, high-confidence commands.

Examples:
	•	open gallery
	•	run goblin
	•	stop render
	•	next image
	•	delete selected
	•	search dragons

These should go:

voice -> transcript -> c parser -> execute

No LLM. No delay. No ambiguity. No token cost.

⸻

Lane 2: drafted CDI path

For anything:
	•	long
	•	compositional
	•	ambiguous
	•	parameterized
	•	involving lookup
	•	involving multiple steps

Examples:
	•	make a goblin sprite on gray background and reduce to six colors
	•	search my local docs for wan22 latent notes and summarize them
	•	build a looping two character dialogue scene then show me the cdi before running

These should go:

voice -> transcript -> parse/classify -> local lookup -> llm drafts CDI -> user previews UI/CDI -> execute

That split is very good.

⸻

Why this works

Because it respects two different truths:

Truth 1

Some commands are so short and common that involving an LLM is wasteful and harmful.

Truth 2

Some commands are too rich to encode well in a rigid parser, but can be compiled into a rigid executable representation afterward.

So the LLM is not the executor.
It is the drafting layer.

That is the correct role.

⸻

Canonical artifacts

You should formalize these artifact types.

1. voice_audio

Raw spoken input.

2. voice_transcript

Speech-to-text output, with confidence and timestamps.

3. command_parse

Result of the pure C parser:
	•	matched command or not
	•	confidence
	•	extracted short-form args

4. route_decision

Decision:
	•	pure_c
	•	llm_draft_required

5. lookup_context

Local files, indexes, command docs, generator library matches, prior known entities.

6. llm_draft_prompt

The exact prompt sent to the local LLM to draft CDI.

7. draft_cdi

The first generated CDI.

8. approved_cdi

The CDI after user preview/edit/confirmation.

9. execution_log

The actual result of running it.

10. result_artifact

Produced outputs.

This is the minimum logging chain that gives you real debuggability.

⸻

Routing logic

This needs to be explicit.

Step 1: transcript

Speech model produces text.

Step 2: short-command parser in C

The parser asks:
	•	is this a known command?
	•	is it short enough?
	•	is argument structure obvious?
	•	is confidence high enough?

If yes:
	•	route to pure C execution

If no:
	•	route to LLM drafting flow

Step 3: local lookup before LLM

Before calling the LLM, gather:
	•	matching generator names
	•	command docs
	•	UI state
	•	current selection
	•	likely relevant local files or encyclopedia entries

This is critical.
The LLM should draft from grounded local context, not just the transcript.

⸻

Very important architectural rule

The LLM should output CDI, not imperative actions

Not:
	•	"click this"
	•	"do that"
	•	"probably use model X"

But:
	•	a strict CDI draft

That keeps the system bounded and inspectable.

So the LLM is a compiler front-end, not an agent wandering around the app.

That’s much safer and cleaner.

⸻

UI / CDI dual preview

This part is especially strong:

user can preview both ui or cdi before execution

That should be a first-class feature, not an advanced toggle.

Because it means:
	•	nontechnical users see a visual plan
	•	technical users inspect exact code
	•	both are looking at the same thing

That is rare and powerful.

Good UX phrasing

The system could say:

I drafted a generator. Preview as:
	•	Visual plan
	•	CDI

Or for more complex flows:

I drafted a pipeline. Review before running.

Then the user can inspect:
	•	model
	•	prompt sections
	•	steps
	•	tools
	•	outputs

⸻

Flow shape: top to bottom

You said:

ui and cdi similar, flows top to bottom

That is excellent.

It means the UI should not be some abstract node graph first.
It should be a vertical reading of the same system.

So if CDI looks like:

$$$generate-sprite
$$prompt
$char
short green goblin

$background
on a gray featureless background

$$$reduce-palette
$$tool
$colors
6

Then the UI should feel like:
	1.	Generate sprite
	•	Character: short green goblin
	•	Background: gray featureless background
	2.	Reduce palette
	•	Colors: 6

Same order. Same structure. Same mental model.

That makes roundtripping much easier.

⸻

