Perfect Beast flow.

⸻

Example pipeline: short command

User says:

open gallery

Artifacts

1. transcript

open gallery

2. parser

short_command_match = true
command = open_gallery
confidence = 0.99

3. execution

Pure C. No LLM.

That fast path matters a lot. It keeps the system snappy and sane.

⸻

Local lookups before LLM

This is one of the best parts of your design.

The draft prompt should include local facts like:
	•	currently selected artifact
	•	current model
	•	current view
	•	generator library names
	•	docs for "reduce palette"
	•	known aliases

So if user says:

make the goblin uglier and loop it

The system can look up:
	•	the current goblin generator
	•	what "loop it" means in Beast context
	•	existing loop-capable pipelines

Then draft CDI grounded in reality.

Without local lookup, the LLM will hallucinate app capabilities.

With lookup, it becomes a compiler assistant.

⸻

Logging and reproducibility

You said:

each intermediate step logged and reproducible to see where went wrong if goes wrong

Yes. This should be a core law.

Proposed law

Every transformation of spoken intent into execution must produce an inspectable artifact.

Then debugging becomes easy:
	•	transcript wrong → speech problem
	•	short parser misrouted → parser problem
	•	bad lookup context → retrieval problem
	•	bad CDI draft → LLM/compiler problem
	•	UI mismatch → rendering problem
	•	output mismatch → execution problem

That’s the kind of system where bugs become tractable.

⸻

Suggested standard generators for voice pipelines

You’ll want a small standard library.

transcribe-voice

Audio → transcript

parse-short-command

Transcript → route decision + parsed command

lookup-command-context

Transcript + app state → grounded context

draft-cdi

Transcript + context → CDI

render-cdi-preview

CDI → UI preview state

approve-cdi

Preview → approved CDI

execute-cdi

Approved CDI → outputs

Even if some are implemented in C and some in LLMs, they still fit the same generator model.

⸻

Security / safety benefit

This architecture is also safer than raw agent execution.

Because the LLM is not just "doing things."

It is:
	•	drafting a bounded artifact
	•	presenting it
	•	waiting for approval

That’s a much better user contract.

Especially for destructive commands.

Example:

delete all failed renders older than a week

The LLM should draft the CDI or action plan, and user approves it.

⸻

Strong naming idea

You might frame this whole subsystem as:

Voice → Draft → Approve → Execute

That is clean and memorable.

Or more Beastly:

Hear → Draft → Reveal → Run

But functionally I’d still document it as:
	•	Hear
	•	Parse
	•	Lookup
	•	Draft
	•	Preview
	•	Approve
	•	Execute

⸻

Key Beast insight

This system turns voice control from:
	•	brittle command parsing
	•	or black-box AI guessing

into:

spoken intent compiled into inspectable code

That is powerful.

⸻

One-line summary

A Beast voice pipeline converts spoken intent into approved executable CDI through a reproducible sequence of transcript, parse, lookup, draft, and preview artifacts.

